Digit blastema characterization through bioimage analysis

Melissa Miller

The work below was done in support of (Griffiths et al. 2025). The overall goal of this work was to characterize the regenerating axolotl digit blastema and its similarity to the regenerating limb blastema. The analyses presented below can also be applied to various projects utilizing fluorescence microscopy.

Figure 1, S4

The first goal of characterizing the digit blastema was to assess whether the regenerating digit expresses the same genes we expect blastemal cells to express. These include genes associated with connective tissue de- and re-differentiation, tissue patterning, and several developmental pathways such as Wnt.

qPCR

Below is an analysis of qPCR data to quantify the presence of, in this case, Indian hedgehog ( Ihh ), which is important for joint morphogenesis. Results of this analysis, as well as for many other genes, are published in (Griffiths et al. 2025).

Data processing

Data used here derives from qPCR targeting Ihh in several regenerating tissues. The regenerating wrist is used as a control against which regenerating digits are compared. The axolotl forelimb has four digits, and each are quantified independently for Ihh expression owing to potential anterior-posterior expression differences.

Raw data
ihh <- read.csv("../knitData/ihh.csv") %>%
  select(1,2,4) %>%
  `colnames<-`(c("Sample", "Target", "CqMean"))
Preparing plot data
ihh <- ihh %>%
  filter(str_detect(Sample,"Met_",negate = T)) %>%
  mutate(Replicate = gsub("^.*_","",Sample)) %>%
  mutate(Sample = gsub("_.*$","",Sample)) %>%
  mutate(Sample = case_when(Sample == "Digit 1" ~ "DI",
                            Sample == "Digit 2" ~ "DII",
                            Sample == "Digit 3" ~ "DIII",
                            Sample == "Digit 4" ~ "DIV",
                            Sample == "Blast" ~ "Wrist")) %>%
  mutate(CqMean = case_when(is.na(CqMean) ~ 40,
                            TRUE ~ CqMean)) %>% # Non-detectable expression is assigned 40
  pivot_wider(., names_from = Target, values_from = CqMean)

ihh <- ihh %>%
  mutate(deltaCt = Ihh-Ef1a) %>%
  filter(Ef1a < 30)
# Used to calculate deltaDeltaCt, a measure of expression change compared to control
std.val <- ihh %>% 
  filter(Sample == "Wrist") %>% 
  select(deltaCt) %>%
  mutate(deltaCt = as.numeric(deltaCt)) %>%
  as.list() %>% unlist() %>%
  mean()

ihh <- ihh %>%
  mutate(deltaDeltaCt = as.numeric(deltaCt)-std.val) %>%
  mutate(logFoldChange = 2^(-1*deltaDeltaCt))

Analysis

Plot

This plots depicts the expression of Ihh across samples on a log-10 scale, relative to the expression of Ef1a.

ggplot(ihh, aes(x = factor(Sample, levels = c("Wrist", "DI", "DII", "DIII", "DIV")), 
                 y = logFoldChange)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.5) +
  geom_boxplot(outliers = FALSE) +
  geom_point(size = 0.5) +
  xlab(NULL) +
  ylab("Relative expression") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(family = "Arial", color = "black", size = 12),
        axis.title = element_text(family = "Arial", color = "black", size = 12),
        panel.border = element_rect(linewidth = 0.5))

Parametric testing

Statistical testing is performed on the expression of Ihh in each sample relative to Ef1a. One-way ANOVA was performed to identify differences in the group, followed by a post hoc Tukey test as necessary. In this case, there is no statistically significant difference indicated by the ANOVA, so a post hoc test is not performed.

ihh.lm <- aov(deltaCt ~ Sample, 
                  data = ihh)
anova(ihh.lm)
Nonparametric testing

Although not used in this publication, nonparametric tests can also be used to analyze qPCR data. Similarly to the parametric tests, there is no significant difference among groups, so the pairwise Wilcox test post hoc is not necessary.

kruskal.test(deltaCt ~ Sample,
             data = ihh)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  deltaCt by Sample
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 4.2059, df = 4, p-value = 0.3789

Figure 2

Given that forelimb regeneration is dependent on an intact nerve supply, the next goal was to demonstrate that digit regeneration is similarly nerve dependent.

mAG vs mCherry

The purpose of this analysis is to partly assess the response of the digit blastema to denervation. Denervation of the regenerating limb leads to a loss in cell cycling and delayed or failed regeneration. Images were taken of a transgenic FUCCI line of animals wherein cells in S or G2 express mAG and cells in G1 express mCherry (Duerr et al. 2022).

Preparing data

A timecourse was captured in regenerating innervated and denervated digits from FUCCI animals. Images of digit blastemas were segmented with Cellpose [(Stringer et al. 2021), (Pachitariu and Stringer 2022), (Stringer and Pachitariu 2025)]. The resulting text outlines were used to measure fluorescence intensity in the mAG and mCherry channels. The measurements were used to classify cells as mAG or mCherry positive as an indication of their cell cycle state.

summary.stats <- read.xlsx("../knitData/mesenchyme_stats.xlsx", 
                           sheetIndex = 1)

summary.stats <- summary.stats %>%
  group_by(Animal, Treatment, Timepoint) %>%
  mutate(total_cells = sum(mAG_total, mCherry_total)) %>%
  mutate(prop_mAG = (mAG_total/total_cells)*100,
         prop_mCherry = (mCherry_total/total_cells)*100)

The data were further processed for the average number of cells in each condition expressing mAG or mCherry.

chart.data <- summary.stats %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  pivot_longer(., c(4,5), names_to = "Channel") %>%
  mutate(Channel = case_when(Channel == "mAG_total" ~ "mAG",
                             TRUE ~ "mCherry")) %>%
  select(1:3, 7:8, 4:6)

colnames(chart.data) <- c(colnames(chart.data)[1:4], "Count", colnames(chart.data)[6:8])

chart.data <- chart.data %>%
  mutate(Treatment = case_when(Treatment == "Dnv" ~ "Denervated",
                               TRUE ~ "Innervated")) %>%
  rename("Innervation" = "Treatment")
count.averages <- chart.data %>%
  select(1:6) %>%
  group_by(Innervation, Timepoint, Channel) %>%
  mutate(Average_Total = mean(Count),
         Innervation = case_when(Innervation == "Innervated" ~ "INV",
                                 TRUE ~ "DNV"),
         Timepoint = case_when(Timepoint == 0 ~ 6,
                               Timepoint == 1 ~ 9,
                               Timepoint == 2 ~ 12,
                               Timepoint == 3 ~ 15,
                               Timepoint == 4 ~ 18,
                               TRUE ~ 21)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  dplyr::select(Channel, Innervation, Timepoint, Average_Total) %>%
  unique() %>%
  dplyr::rename(Average = Average_Total)

This chart shows that following amputation, innervated digits display a small, transitory loss in cell cycling associated with tissue degradation, followed by a “recovery”. In contrast, denervated digits do not display this same recovery, and the proportion of cycling cells continues to decline as cells arrest in G1.

Cell cycling timecourse statistics

We are interested in showing that there is no significant difference in the proportion of cycling cells at any time in the innervated digits, depicted below.

summary.INV <- summary.stats %>% 
  filter(Treatment == "Inv") %>% 
  arrange(Timepoint)
ggplot(summary.INV, aes(x = Timepoint, y = prop_mAG, group = Timepoint)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_point()

Using a Kruskal-Wallis rank-sum test, we conclude that there is no significant difference in the proportion of cycling cells between any timepoints in innervated samples.

kruskal.test(prop_mAG ~ Timepoint, summary.INV)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  prop_mAG by Timepoint
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 7.5356, df = 5, p-value = 0.1838

For the denervated, we hope to determine that there is a difference in the proportion of cycling cells, namely that the proportion continually decreases and is significantly lower at later timepoints than in the first collection.

summary.DNV <- summary.stats %>% 
  filter(Treatment == "Dnv") %>% 
  arrange(Timepoint)
ggplot(summary.DNV, aes(x = Timepoint, y = prop_mAG, group = Timepoint)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_point()

The Kruskal-Wallis test indicates that there exists significant differences in the proportion of cycling cells between timepoints.

kruskal.test(prop_mAG ~ Timepoint, summary.DNV)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  prop_mAG by Timepoint
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 16.556, df = 5, p-value = 0.005423

Because we want to see that there is a significant decrease in the proportion of cycling cells between time 0 (6dpa) and time 5 (21dpa), we perform a Wilcoxon rank sum exact test with a “g” alternative. We find that the proportion of cycling cells at time 0 is significantly greater than the proportion of cycling cells at time 5, supporting our earlier conclusion that denervated digits do not display a “recovery” in G1 arrest.

wilcox.test(summary.DNV[summary.DNV$Timepoint == 0,]$prop_mAG,
            summary.DNV[summary.DNV$Timepoint == 5,]$prop_mAG,
            p.adjust = "fdr",
            alternative = "g")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  summary.DNV[summary.DNV$Timepoint == 0, ]$prop_mAG and summary.DNV[summary.DNV$Timepoint == 5, ]$prop_mAG
## W = 12, p-value = 0.02857
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is greater than 0

INV vs. DNV cell count timecourse

Taking what we found with regard to the G1 arrest seen in denervated digits, we wanted to show that there is a similar loss in the total cells present in the tissue over time as denervated tissue degrades.

totals <- chart.data %>%

This chart shows that in the denervated samples, the total number of cells in the tissue continues to drop over time, aligning with the observed G1 arrest. In innervated samples, there is moderate tissue degradation as injured cells are cleared out, but this is followed by a rebound in cell cycling which leads to an increased number of cells present.

Cell count statistics

We show here that the total number of cells in the denervated digits over time can be fit to a linear curve indicating a downward trend. We show similarly that in innervated digits, a linear curve is not well fitted, represented by a very low R-squared. While not shown here, we found that the total number of cells in the innervated digits is best fit by a second-degree polynomial curve, representing the observed rebound in cell numbers.

Cell cycle state

Next, we sought to more closely resolve the cell cycle stage 15dpa innervated and denervated digit blastemas occupy. This was done by application of several immunofluorescent markers for the different cell cycle stages; distinct combinations of these markers indicate a cell’s current stage.

Preparing data

results.path <- "../knitData/mesenchyme"
files <- Sys.glob( file.path( results.path, "*.xlsx" ) )

cc.data <- data.frame()
for(file in files){
  baseFilename <- basename( file_path_sans_ext(file) )
  animal <- unlist( str_split( baseFilename, "_") )[[2]]
  condition <- unlist( str_split( baseFilename, "_") )[[3]]
  
  df <- read.xlsx(file, sheetName = "Sheet2")
  colnames(df) <- c("Identity", "Count")
  
  total_cells = colSums(df %>% select(Count))
  df <- df %>%
    mutate(Animal = animal, 
           Condition = condition,
           cellNum = total_cells)
  
  cc.data <- rbind(cc.data, df)
}
# Categorizing cells based on their combinations of markers
g0 <- c("pH-,mC-,mA-,Ed-")
g1 <- c("pH-,mC+,mA-,Ed-")
s <- c("pH-,mC-,mA+,Ed+", "pH-,mC+,mA-,Ed+", 
       "pH-,mC-,mA-,Ed+", "pH-,mC+,mA+,Ed+",
       "pH-,mC+,mA+,Ed-")
g2 <- c("pH-,mC-,mA+,Ed-")
m <- c("pH+,mC-,mA+,Ed-", "pH+,mC+,mA+,Ed-",
       "pH+,mC+,mA-,Ed-", "pH+,mC-,mA-,Ed-")

chart.data <- cc.data %>%
  mutate(new.ident = (case_when(Identity %in% g1 ~ "G1",
                                Identity %in% s ~ "S",
                                Identity %in% g2 ~ "G2",
                                Identity %in% m ~ "M",
                                Identity %in% g0 ~ "G0")),
         Condition = (case_when(Condition == "Inv" ~ "INV",
                                TRUE ~ "DNV"))) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(new.ident)) %>%
  select(3, 4, 6, 2, 5) %>%
  group_by(Animal, Condition, new.ident, cellNum) %>%
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) %>%
  select(Animal, Condition, new.ident, Total, cellNum)
total.cells <- chart.data %>% 
  group_by(Condition) %>% 
  summarise(total_cells = sum(cellNum))
merged <- left_join(chart.data, 
                    total.cells, 
                    by = c("Condition")) %>% 
  mutate(prop = round((Total/total_cells)*100, 3)) %>% 
  select(Animal, Condition, new.ident, prop) %>%
  `colnames<-`(c("Animal", "Condition", "Identity", "Proportion"))
chart.data <- chart.data %>%
  mutate(total_cells = case_when(Condition == "INV" ~ 2500,
                                 Condition == "DNV" ~ 1950)) %>% 
  group_by(Condition, new.ident, total_cells) %>%
  summarize(cell_total = sum(Total)) %>% 
  mutate(prop = round((cell_total/total_cells)*100, 2))

APOEB

We next sought to assess the presence of immune cells in innervated and denervated digit blastemas. Macrophages are an essential component of limb regeneration (Godwin, Pinto, and Rosenthal 2013), but they can contribute to abberant fibrosis and scarring in a denervated limb. #### Preparing data

results.path <- "../knitData/apoeb"
files <- Sys.glob( file.path( results.path, "G*.xlsx" ) )
apoeb.data <- data.frame()

# A separate characterization for autofluorescent blood cells was done
# in order to remove them from the analysis.
RBCs <- read.xlsx("../knitData/thresholds_and_RBCs.xlsx", 
                  sheetIndex = 1) %>%
  pivot_longer(.,3:14) %>% 
  select(1, 2, 4) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  select(1,3) %>%
  `colnames<-`(c("Sample", "RBC_ID")) %>% 
  separate_wider_delim(., 1, delim = "_", names_sep = "_") %>%
  `colnames<-`(c("Replicate", "Condition", "RBC_ID")) %>%
  mutate(Replicate = paste0("A",Replicate),
         Condition = str_to_upper(Condition)) %>%
  mutate(RBC_ID = as.character(RBC_ID))

for(file in files){
  baseFilename <- basename( file_path_sans_ext(file) )
  replicate <- unlist( str_split( baseFilename, "_") )[[2]]
  condition <- unlist( str_split( baseFilename, "_") )[[3]]
  
  df <- read.xlsx(file, sheetIndex = 1) %>%
    select(1, 2)
  num_cells <- nrow(df)
  colnames(df) <- c("Cell_ID", "Mean_Intensity")
  df <- df %>%
    mutate(Replicate = replicate, 
           Condition = str_to_upper(condition),
           total_cells = num_cells) %>%
    mutate(Cell_ID = gsub("Segment #","",Cell_ID),
           state = case_when(Mean_Intensity >= 6127.6875 ~ "positive",
                             TRUE ~ "negative")) %>%
    mutate(Cell_ID = gsub(" \\(nuclei\\)", "", Cell_ID)) %>%
    mutate(Cell_ID = gsub(" \\(Cellpose-based Segmenter\\)","",Cell_ID))
  
  rbc.data <- RBCs %>%
    filter(Replicate == replicate & 
             Condition == str_to_upper(condition))
  
  df <- df %>%
    mutate(state = case_when(Cell_ID %in% RBCs$RBC_ID ~ "negative",
                             TRUE ~ state))
  
  apoeb.data <- rbind(apoeb.data, df)
  
}
apoeb.data <- apoeb.data %>%
  select(-Mean_Intensity)
pos.data <- apoeb.data %>%
  filter(state == "positive") %>%
  group_by(Replicate, Condition, total_cells) %>%
  summarise(num_positive = n())
pos.data <- pos.data %>%
  mutate(pct.pos = (num_positive/total_cells)*100) %>%
  mutate(pct.pos = round(pct.pos, 2))

Hedgehog signaling

The Hedgehog signaling pathway is important for correct joint morphology. We sought to examine the role of Hedgehog signaling in digit regeneration and its role in joint reformation. To that end, animals were amputated at the wrist or at the digit level and treated with a DMSO control, cyclopamine (a Hedgehog inhibitor), and smoothened agonist (SAG; a Hedgehog activator), then assessed for distal joint formation.

hedgehog.data <- read.xlsx("../knitData/Jackson_digits_cleaned.xlsx", 
                           sheetIndex = 3) %>%
  mutate(Digit_num = case_when(Digit_num == 1 ~ "I",
                               Digit_num == 2 ~ "II",
                               Digit_num == 3 ~ "III",
                               Digit_num == 4 ~ "IV"),
         grid = case_when(Treatment == "Control" ~ paste0("Control ", Amp_plane),
                          Treatment == "Cyclo" ~ "Digit + Cyclopamine",
                          Treatment == "SAG" ~ "Digit + SAG"))

We see that, as noted before, digit amputations exhibit overall lower fidelity in joint regeneration compared to more proximal amputations, and that this fidelity varies across digits. Further, none of the digits in which the Hedgehog signaling pathway was interrupted via cyclopamine treatment regenerated their joints. However, activation of Hedgehog signaling with SAG was not itself sufficient to promote regenerative fidelity.

Other

The main goals of this analysis were to explore whether there is a difference in relative regenerated lengths of each digit, and to consider if the regenerated tissue is a different length with or without a regenerated joint. Further, groups are included which are treated with SAG, a hedgehog agonist, and Cyclopamine, a hedgehog signaling inhibitor, to determine the role of hedgehog signaling in joint regeneration fidelity. These analyses were ultimately not included in the publication owing to the inability to meaningfully analyze the impact of joint regeneration on digit length.

Note that lot of data cleaning needs to be done to be able to use this data. These measurements were collected by two separate students in the lab and are processed independently, then combined.

Overall digit length

Statistics

We first perform a Kruskal-Wallis test for each digit to determine if there exists any difference between wrist controls and digit amputations.

digits <- c("DI", "DII", "DIII", "DIV")
conditions <- c("Wrist", "Control", "SAG", "Cyclopamine")

for(digit in digits){
  kw.data <- merged %>% drop_na() %>% filter(Digit == digit)
  print(paste0("Kruskal-Wallis for ", digit))
  res <- kruskal.test(Length ~ Condition, kw.data)
  print(res["p.value"])
}
## [1] "Kruskal-Wallis for DI"
## $p.value
## [1] 2.962337e-10
## 
## [1] "Kruskal-Wallis for DII"
## $p.value
## [1] 6.760125e-13
## 
## [1] "Kruskal-Wallis for DIII"
## $p.value
## [1] 2.159442e-09
## 
## [1] "Kruskal-Wallis for DIV"
## $p.value
## [1] 8.343479e-11

Because the Kruskal-Wallis test indicated significant differences in all groups, we follow up with a Wilcoxon test to determine pairwise differences between digits.

wt.results <- data.frame()
for(digit in digits){
  kw.data <- merged %>% drop_na() %>% filter(Digit == digit)
  for(condition1 in conditions){
    for(condition2 in conditions){
      if(!condition1 == condition2){
      res <- wilcox.test(Length ~ Condition, kw.data,
                     subset = Condition %in% c(condition1, condition2))
      add <- c(Digit = digit, Condition1 = condition1, 
               Condition2 = condition2, p.val = res["p.value"])
      wt.results <- rbind(wt.results, add)
      }
    }
  }
}

  theme(legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "bottom",

Statistics

Statistical testing with this dataset is a challenge, given that in many cases there is no comparison; i.e., all digits regenerated with/out a joint. Testing is done below only for cases where some digits regenerated with and without a joint.

print(paste0("Control digit 1 Yes joint vs. No joint: ",
             wilcox.test(Length ~ Has_joint, 
            merged,
            subset = Condition == "Control" & Digit == "DI")["p.value"]))
## [1] "Control digit 1 Yes joint vs. No joint: 0.0283400809716599"
print(paste0("Wilcox for SAG digit 1 Yes joint vs. No joint: ",
            wilcox.test(Length ~ Has_joint, 
            merged,
            subset = Condition == "SAG" & Digit == "DI")["p.value"]))
## [1] "Wilcox for SAG digit 1 Yes joint vs. No joint: 0.421052631578947"

             wilcox.test(Length ~ Has_joint, 
            merged,
            subset = Condition == "Control" & Digit == "DII")["p.value"]))
## [1] "Wilcox for Control digit 2 Yes joint vs. No joint: 0.0467836257309941"
print(paste0("Wilcox for SAG digit 2 Yes joint vs. No joint: ",
             wilcox.test(Length ~ Has_joint, 
            merged,
            subset = Condition == "SAG" & Digit == "DII")["p.value"]))
## [1] "Wilcox for SAG digit 2 Yes joint vs. No joint: 0.00361197110423117"
